{{otherpersons|John Kinnear}}
'''John Boyd Kinnear''' (1828 <U+2013> 10 November 1920) was a Scottish lawyer, writer and radical [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.

Kinnear was the son of Charles Kinnear of Kinloch and his wife Christian Boyd Greenshields. He was educated at [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh University]] and [[University of St Andrews|St Andrews University]]. He became a Scottish Advocate in 1850 and from 1852 to 1856 was political secretary to the [[Lord Advocate]] of Scotland  [[James Moncreiff, 1st Baron Moncreiff|James Moncreiff]]. In 1855 he was  called to the bar at [[Inner Temple]] and was a [[Justice of the Peace|J.P.]] <ref>[http://www.archive.org/stream/debrettshouseo1886londuoft Debretts Guide to the House of Commons 1886]</ref> He was an extensive writer on jurisprudence and other topics including religion and women's rights.<ref>[http://openlibrary.org/a/OL1861361A/John_Boyd_Kinnear Open Library - John Boyd Kinnear]</ref> 

In the [[United Kingdom general election, 1885|1885 general election]], he was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for East Fife.<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Fcommons.htm Leigh Rayment]</ref> However in [[United Kingdom general election, 1886|1886]] he stood as a [[Liberal Unionist]] and was defeated by future prime minister [[Herbert Asquith]].<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=C5uWTJ-xWEUC&pg=PA275&lpg=PA275&dq=%22Boyd-Kinnear%22+Fife&source=bl&ots=WWm1ViAtKb&sig=wwpdvNsP1sN_yI5FaEwL8kVlEsA&hl=en&ei=_i7GSqrFEcPRjAfoyeQ5&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6#v=onepage&q=%22Boyd-Kinnear%22%20Fife&f=false  George W. Russell ''Politics and Personalities, with Other Essays'']</ref>

Kinnear died at the age of  92.

Kinnear married Sarah Harriet Frith in 1852. She died in 1866 and he married secondly in 1868, Teresa Bassano of Venice.

==Publications==
*''A comparison of the bankruptcy systems of England and Scotland'' W. Maxwell, 1858  
*''Suggestions relative to the improvement of Court of Session procedure'' Bell and Bradfute, 1863  
*''Digest of House of Lords cases decided on appeal from Scotland, 1709 to 1864'' Bell & Bradfute, 1865  
*''The right of women to labour'' F. Bell, 1873   
*''Principles of property in land'' Smith, Elder, 1880  
* ''Principles of Civil Government'' Smith, Elder & Co., 1887  
*''The education of women'' Women's Emancipation Union, 1892  
*''The foundations of religion'' Smith, Elder, 1905  

